Scientists have found an animal that can live for 500 years
An international group of biologists has come to the conclusion that the longest-living vertebrate animal is the Greenlandic polar shark, which can live for about 500 years, reports RT.
Scientists have carried out radiocarbon analysis of the lens of the eye of 28 Greenland sharks.
The largest shark, which is more than five meters in length, can be from 272 to 512 years old.
Biologists believe that low metabolism, which leads to slow development, plays an important role in shark longevity.
Female harp sharks only reach sexual maturity by the age of 150.
Earlier it was believed that the shark&#39;s &quot;neighbor&quot;, the bowhead whale, lives the longest of all vertebrates.
The oldest specimen known to scientists was just over 210 years old.
