Signs of the end.
What indicates that Russia is emerging from the crisis?
Economists have seen signs of Russia&#39;s emerging from its longest recession in twenty years.
According to analysts interviewed by Bloomberg, Russia&#39;s GDP is showing positive dynamics - in the second quarter, GDP fell by 0.8% on an annualized basis.
This figure is the lowest since the beginning of 2015.
According to the latest data from Rosstat, the decline in the Russian economy in the second quarter slowed down to 0.6%.
The Central Bank and the Ministry of Economic Development have also recently announced the stabilization of the situation.
Slow growth ahead.
According to CBR experts, the recession in the Russian economy is a thing of the past.
&quot;The index estimate of the Russian GDP suggests that the recession is over, and ahead is the slow growth of the economy,&quot; the Bank of Russia&#39;s bulletin &quot;What Trends Talk About&quot; says.
The regulator&#39;s specialists increased the modular estimate of GDP for the current quarter to 0.4%, the estimate for the fourth quarter is 0.5%.
According to a representative of the Ministry of Economic Development and Trade, during the second quarter, the decline in the RF GDP stopped in the second quarter, amounting to 0.2%.
In the second quarter, the seasonally adjusted GDP decline was 0.2% qoq.
But during the quarter the decline stopped: in April it amounted to 0.2%, and in May and June the change in GDP was within the range of 0-0.15, &quot;RIA Novosti quotes a representative of the Ministry of Economic Development.
The slowdown in the decline of the Russian economy over the past five quarters indicates that the bottom has been passed.
Among other markers that indicate signs of a revival in the national economy, Bloomberg calls the growth in demand for electricity and rail transport, the revival of business.
If we make an allowance for the fact that the year is a leap year, then it is clear that the dynamics of plus 1% of electricity consumption can be half due to the additional working day.
Add to this the lower average annual temperature in the first quarter.
The next argument is the growth of freight traffic, but it is difficult to obtain accurate data here, and plus or minus 0.5% of the semi-annual volume can also be explained by seasonality, &quot;explains Kirill Yakovenko from ALOR BROKER.
However, there are other, more obvious signs of the stabilization of the Russian economy.
For example, lowering price pressures.
In July, the CPI stood at 7.2%, up from 15.6% in the same month last year.
Moreover, the last two weeks Rosstat has been recording deflation.
Prices in Russia fell for the first time in five years.
If you look at the dynamics of the ruble exchange rate, which, although it showed strong fluctuations at the beginning of the year, has strengthened by 12% in August since the beginning of the year.
This is also one of the signs of recovery, followed by indicators from the real sector of the economy &quot;, - emphasizes Yakovenko.
In addition, an increase in industrial production has been observed in the Russian Federation since April.
In June, the figure rose by 1.7%.
The rate of decline in foreign trade turnover is slowing down from -32.8% in January 2016 to -20.7% in May.
The situation on the labor market also demonstrates positive dynamics, where the unemployment rate dropped to 5.4%.
It was lower only in September 2015 (5.2%).
Despite the favorable situation on the labor market, the issue with the real disposable income of the population leaves much to be desired.
In annual terms, the indicator is down 4.8%.
This factor can impede economic recovery, as household spending makes a significant contribution to GDP.
As a rule, their share in the structure of the economy exceeds 50%.
In addition to low consumer activity, the tough policy of the Bank of Russia can also be named as risk factors for economic growth.
The regulator keeps the rate at 10.5%, which does not have the best effect on the real sector.
An insufficiently high level of investment is also a negative factor, which hinders the development of industrial potential.
But in general, it can be assumed that by the end of the year the rate of decline in the Russian economy will slow down to -0.5% against -3.7% in 2015, &quot;says Irina Rogova, an analyst at Forex Club.
The process of naturalization of athletes, recently launched in Russian football and well-established in winter sports at the Sochi Olympics, is not yet so actively developed in summer sports.
If former foreigners compete in the Olympic Games in Rio for Russia, then in most cases we are talking about natives of countries - the former republics of the Soviet Union.
But in Rio de Janeiro, we can observe the opposite process - a fairly large number of Russians are flying the flags of other states.
In each case, the history of the change of citizenship is different.
Some were taken to another country by their parents in childhood, leaving no choice.
Someone could not stand the competition for a place in the Russian team.
And someone thought that the best conditions for development in sports would be created abroad.
AiF.ru has found at least 16 athletes who have decided to change their Russian citizenship.
The German passport of a 27-year-old girl says that her name is Lisa Ryzhikh.
But earlier she was, of course, Elizabeth.
She was born in 1988 in the city of Omsk.
Just four years later, as soon as the Soviet Union collapsed, Lisa&#39;s parents decided to emigrate to Germany.
The girl had no choice.
There she decided to follow in the footsteps of her older sister - to take up athletics.
Like her sister, Lisa chose pole vaulting.
If she had stayed in Russia, she would hardly have been able to &quot;move from the throne&quot; Elena Isinbaeva.
Unfortunately, at the Olympics in Rio, Lisa will be the only our countrywoman, albeit a former one, in the pole vault sector.
Her best achievements in this sport are the bronze of the 2010 European Championship and the silver of the continental championship in 2016, which she won again in the absence of Elena Isinbayeva.
Elena Pirozhkova, 29, was born in Novokuznetsk in 1986.
Her parents are religious evangelical propagandists.
Largely because of their faith, they left for the United States when the girl was only three years old.
In addition to Elena, eight more children grew up in the family.
They all lived in the small town of Greenfield, Massachusetts.
Lena began to get involved in wrestling at school.
Showing good results, she moved to Colorado Springs, where she continued her studies at the US Wrestling Training Center under the guidance of another former Russian, Vladislav Izboinikov.
At the 2012 London Olympics, Elena lost her first fight.
But at the World Championships in the same year - a victory.
Before that, by the way, she managed to win silver at the 2010 world championship.
After that, there were bronze in 2013 and silver in 2014.
26-year-old Maria was born in the city of Yaroslavl, where she first got acquainted with synchronized swimming.
But it would be wrong to say that she was brought up by our coaches in Russia.
Soon the girl&#39;s family decided to emigrate to the United States and settle in the city of Colorado.
There Maria continued her studies.
Soon she was already part of the US national team and showed excellent results at the Pan American Games.
It is clear that at a serious international level it cannot compete with Russian synchronized swimmers, but for America its indicators are the ceiling.
Kristina Shaldybina received a new name, which sounds strange in Russian, at the age of 11, when her parents decided to continue training the girl in rhythmic gymnastics overseas.
Until this moment, the girl was engaged in her favorite sport in her native Yaroslavl.
After emigrating to the United States, she quickly entered the youth team of this country, and later broke into the main national team.
At the Pan American Games, 19-year-old Kristen won gold and silver.
Of course, she did not have to fight for the first positions on the world stage, but for the USA she organized a real breakthrough - she brought the Stars and Stripes team to the Olympic Games in Rio de Janeiro.
Another former &quot;artist&quot; of ours is Yana Berezko-Margrander, who plays for the German national team.
Yana was born in Togliatti.
In 2008, when the girl was 13 years old, the family decided to move to Germany - there the girl had more prospects of getting into the national team.
She soon represented her country at the 2012 London Olympics.
There, however, Yana was able to take only 17th place, not enough to get into the final competitions in the individual championship.
But two years before that, she managed to win the bronze medal of the Olympic Youth Games.
Another gymnast, only this time athletic - Irina Sazonova.
If the ways of emigration of the athletes mentioned earlier can be called standard, then the choice of Irina&#39;s family is very unusual - Iceland.
Ira is a pupil of the Volgograd sports school.
Naturally, in Iceland, she immediately became the champion of the country.
True, Ira still trains in Russia - she comes to her homeland on purpose so as not to lose her skills.
In Rio, she did not perform as well as she would like.
The best place is 40 in individual all-around.
There is very little information about the swimmer Maria Ugolkova in the Russian information space.
For a very long time, Maria has been living and training in Switzerland.
However, for a long time, she performed under the Russian flag, showing good results - there was even a country&#39;s record at a distance of 200 meters butterfly.
In 2015, she received Swiss citizenship and began to compete under the red and white flag.
In Rio, her best performance is 14th in the 4 × 100 complex relay.
To get to the games, the girl launched a crowdfunding project, thanks to which she was able to collect about 6 thousand francs, which allowed her to pay for the preparation for the Olympics.
31-year-old freestyle wrestler Adam Batirov spent almost his entire career under the Russian flag.
During this time, the native of Khasavyurt managed to become a three-time winner of the European Championships, the champion of Russia, and the master of sports of Russia of international class.
When he stopped making his way to our national team, it was time to think about changing citizenship.
For several years, the talented wrestler disappeared from the sports platforms.
The triumphant return took place at the 2016 Asian Championships - Batirov already represented Bahrain, for which he won a gold medal and received a ticket to the Olympics in Rio.
Even less is known at home about another ex-Russian, Mikhail Kudinov, than even about the Swiss swimmer Maria Ugolkova.
The fact is that his parents emigrated from Vladivostok to New Zealand when the boy was very young.
It was there that Mikhail began to engage in artistic gymnastics.
He did not achieve great success at the international level.
In Rio, his best result was 40th in the parallel bars qualification.
But for New Zealand, even getting to the Olympic Games in artistic gymnastics is already a breakthrough.
When Nastya, who was born in Moscow in 1985, was only 9 years old, her family emigrated to Israel.
There, the girl continued her synchronized swimming lessons, showing high results at the national level.
In 2014, at the European Championships in Berlin, the girl took 6th place in synchronized swimming.
In a duet with Evgenia Tetelbaum, Anastasia took eighth place.
In the solo program, she was fifth.
Like Anastasia, 23-year-old Dmitry Kreuter plays for the Israeli national team.
When the boy was only 6 years old, his mother decided to immigrate to Israel.
In 2009, at the age of 17, Dmitry already became the champion of the country.
In the same year, he won the World Youth Championship.
A year later, Kreuter also won gold at the Youth Olympic Games in Singapore.
In addition to high jumps, Dmitry is engaged in long jump and triple jump.
31-year-old Albert is another native of Khasavyurt, who, after long performances for Russia, decided to change his sports citizenship.
However, unlike Batirov, Albert chose Romania, which he will represent in Rio.
In Russia, he played for the School of Higher Sports Excellence in Krasnoyarsk, in 2011 he even became the champion of the country.
28-year-old Oleg Antonov was born in Moscow into the family of the USSR national volleyball team player Yaroslav Antonov.
Literally a year before the birth of his son, Yaroslav was recognized as the best volleyball player on the planet.
He soon decided to pursue a career in Italy.
The family stayed there permanently.
In 2015, as part of the national team, he became the bronze medalist of the European Championship, held on the territory of his new homeland.
Khadzhiev was born in Chechnya in 1994 and ended up with his family in the midst of the war.
Ten years later, the parents decided to emigrate.
The original goal was Norway, but it was not possible to get to this northern country - I had to go to France, to Nice.
There Zelimkhan continued to study freestyle wrestling.
He soon won the junior world championship and later qualified for the Olympic Games.
In Rio, he will be the only representative of France in the wrestling tournament.
And again freestyle wrestling, and again a former Russian.
This time we will talk about a native of North Ossetia who emigrated to Spain - about Taimuraz Friev.
At the end of December 2012, he was awarded Spanish citizenship and currently plays for the national team of that country.
Prior to that, however, the 30-year-old athlete had already achieved high results in Russia.
He became the bronze medalist of the 2007 and 2008 national championships.
Tired of missing the national team, Taimuraz decided to change his sports citizenship.
The last on our list is a Chechen boxer born in 1995 in the capital of Dagestan Makhachkala - Artur Biyarslanov.
When the boy was ten years old, his parents took the family through Azerbaijan to Canada.
There, Arthur, on the advice of his older brother, began boxing.
Since then, Arthur has become the champion of Canada three times, and in 2012 he became the world champion among youth.
In 2015, Biyarslanov won the Pan American Games gold, the first for his new homeland since 1975.
Head of the Presidential Administration of the Russian Federation Anton Vaino.
On Friday, August 12, Vladimir Putin appointed Anton Vaino as head of the Russian presidential administration.
Previously, this position was held by Sergei Ivanov.
&quot;The head of state, by his decree, appointed Anton Vaino the Chief of Staff of the President of the Russian Federation, relieving him of his post,&quot; the decree, signed by Putin and published on the Kremlin&#39;s website, says.
Since May 2012, Vaino has been the Deputy Head of the Presidential Administration of the Russian Federation.
Anton Eduardovich Vaino was born on February 17, 1972 in Tallinn.
Father - Eduard Vaino, chairman of the Cuba-Russia Business Council at the Chamber of Commerce and Industry of the Russian Federation and vice president for external relations and interaction with shareholders of AvtoVAZ.
Grandfather - Karl Vaino - from 1978 to 1988, the first secretary of the Central Committee of the Communist Party of Estonia.
In 1996 he graduated from the Moscow State Institute of International Relations of the Ministry of Foreign Affairs of Russia, Faculty of International Relations.
From 1996 to 2001 he worked at the Russian Embassy in Japan, then at the Second Asia Department of the Russian Foreign Ministry.
From 2002 to 2004, he held various positions in the Protocol Department of the President of the Russian Federation.
From 2004 to 2007 - Deputy Head of the Protocol and Organizational Directorate of the President of the Russian Federation.
From 2007 to 2007 - First Deputy Chief of Protocol of the President of the Russian Federation.
From October 2007 to April 2008 - Deputy Chief of Staff of the Government of the Russian Federation.
On April 25, 2008, he was appointed Head of the Protocol of the Prime Minister of the Russian Federation, Deputy Chief of Staff of the Government of the Russian Federation.
Since December 27, 2011 - Minister of the Russian Federation - Head of the Government Office of the Russian Federation.
On May 22, 2012, he was appointed Deputy Head of the Presidential Administration of the Russian Federation.
Fluent in English and Japanese.
Active State Councilor of the Russian Federation, 1st class (class rank awarded by the Decree of the President of the Russian Federation of January 22, 2008)
Certificate of honor of the President of the Russian Federation (February 16, 2012) for services in supporting the activities of the government of the Russian Federation and many years of conscientious work.
Gratitude of the President of the Russian Federation (November 24, 2005) for merits in the preparation and holding of solemn events dedicated to the 60th anniversary of Victory in the Great Patriotic War.
He is married and has a son.
