A heart attack affects approximately 140,000 people in England every year, and a quarter of them have another attack or stroke.
Heart attacks and strokes result from the buildup of fatty material on the walls of the arteries and the formation of plaque.
If the plaque breaks apart, it can cause a blood clot, blocking blood from reaching the heart and causing a heart attack.
And if the clot moves, it can move along the bloodstream and block blood flow to the brain, causing a stroke.
People who have already had one attack are at greater risk of getting another.
Ticagrelor, manufactured by the British firm AstraZeneca and marketed under the name Brilique, reduces the risk by making blood clots less likely.
