The HACCP system has been mandatory for catering for more than a year, but most cafes and restaurants in St. Petersburg have not yet implemented it.
Checks are becoming more active, and businesses face fines of up to 1 million rubles.
For more than a year now, the Hazard Analysis and Critical Control Points (HACCP, in the Russian version of HACCP) - risk analysis and critical control points - has been mandatory for food manufacturers and carriers, as well as catering companies in Russia, as a member of the Customs Union (CU) ...
Business inspections by Rospotrebnadzor for compliance with these standards in St. Petersburg began in February 2015.
But so far, officials are issuing fines only for certain violations of the regulations (see &quot;List of documents&quot; ...).
Failure to comply with the regulations as a whole will cost the enterprise 600 thousand rubles for the first violation and 1 million rubles for the second.
HACCP, as a system that takes into account the risks of working with food and prevents them, was invented in the United States in the 1960s.
Then it was about the safety of food for astronauts.
Now the system is used in all food enterprises, not only in the United States, but also in Canada and the European Union.
Since February 2015, HACCP has been operating on the territory of the Customs Union.
The business had 4 years to develop and implement the system (the HACCP requirement appeared in the technical regulations of the CU in 2011).
However, both entrepreneurs and officials admit that most companies have not even heard of this rule.
Unfortunately, we have long been convinced that the norm applies only to food production, and not restaurateurs, - explained the head of the Public Council Elena Tsereteli.
Now everyone is trying to catch up.
