The Vinyl End-User: Who Really Buys Records?
Single middle-aged men love vinyl.
And until you rush to litter the comments section with rude insults under the pseudonym Not All Alone Middle Aged Men, this statement is based on evidence.
According to YouGov, so much of the talked about record revival is not driven by the millennial boom looking to embrace the novelty of a tangible subject, but by middle-aged nostalgia.
Those who recently bought a vinyl album are most likely between the ages of 45 and 54, according to the data.
Moreover, those in the 18-24 age group are the least likely.
It is also not just an act of collecting by amateurs - it has an emotional meaning: Older vinyl buyers are slightly more likely to keep their feelings to themselves (56% versus 53%) and enjoy being alone (69% versus 66%).
But are YouGov&#39;s results correct?
If this blog was a TV news report, the camera would follow me as I walked down the middle of busy Soho Street, wearing a modest gray suit and gesticulating violently before stopping, folding my arms and saying something imposing like, “Okay, let&#39;s see . &quot;
So let&#39;s see.
While the heart of Soho is slowly losing its charm and filth - hotels, cafes, Paperchase shops are now swarming with buildings once occupied by independent sellers - a few record stores with fantastic specialists remain.
I would probably ask the camera to stop for the next scene in which I get close to various people in some of these stores and try to gauge their age and emotional state through observation.
Glasgow native Stewart, 55, followed by me from Sister Ray (data count: two young women, three middle-aged men) to Reckless Records (data count: eight middle-aged men, one woman probably over 20), into London for half a day to hold a meeting and shopping for hours.
Is he a collector, I ask?
“I believe so,” he says.
I have about 3,000 or 4,000 records.
These records, pictured above (he emailed me a photo, I didn&#39;t chase him home) line the walls of his living room.
His reason for acquiring such a huge number of albums and singles stems in part from his disposable income: he can now buy records that he could not afford when they first came out and buy back items that he sold when he was young and broke.
&quot;A lot of what I buy is the late 60s, early 70s, things that came out when I was 11 or 12, things that I was probably too young to buy for.&quot; he says.
He agrees that those who buy records are most likely introverts who enjoy their own company, adding, “I don&#39;t smoke, I don&#39;t drink very much.
This is my flaw.
Wez, 25, who works at Sister Ray, also believes that many of the clients he meets fit the YouGov profile.
He, however, noticed a new wave of people influenced by the media hype, people who heard about the comeback and felt a responsibility to buy back their old records.
From the conversations I&#39;ve had, people got rid of their collection, usually around 1998 or 1999.
Customers who once sold their vinyl to buy CDs are now selling their CDs to buy back their records, ”he says.
This may explain the boom among vinyl revivalists of a certain age.
What about the perceived emotional importance of the records?
It is enough to spend a few seconds in a store like Phonica to realize that record stores offer a comfortable company for people with similar views.
Some of the older customers, in particular, are offended by the cashless payment system, Wes said.
Some vinyl lovers may feel overwhelmed by the digital world and prefer to retreat into the permanence of familiar record sleeves, objects that evoke memories of serene youth.
“I think sometimes it can be filling a void or having material things as a kind of tranquility,” says Wes.
Since I am a collector myself, I have it, and I think a lot of people have it too.
This is an easy way to keep your head busy.
“We are like their social workers!” A colleague spoke from the record rack.
An ICM poll in April found that nearly 50% of people who bought a vinyl album in the last month haven&#39;t listened to it yet.
The survey also found that 41% have a turntable they never use, while 7% of those who buy vinyl do not have a turntable.
At this point in the news coverage, I would probably look seriously puzzled as I flip through Bossanov&#39;s collection rack.
The &quot;trophy&quot; aspect of rebirth is what Johnny, 42, who works at Sounds of the Universe (tally: three middle-aged men) noticed.
&quot;Someone came over recently and said, &#39;I don&#39;t have a turntable, but I want to buy a Radiohead record so we can put it on our shelf,&quot; he says.
This is not a large percentage, but it definitely does.
More piece, less music.
We have people who say, &quot;I don&#39;t have a turntable.&quot;
These are younger people, not elderly, they are a little less than twenty, who are just getting to know this.
