French court rejects proposal to demolish shops in Jungle refugee camp
A French court rejected a proposal by the Calais authorities to demolish dozens of makeshift shops and restaurants in the Jungle camp, where thousands of refugees live.
In court hearings this week, Calais officials said the state should be able to demolish a total of 72 homemade shops where people inside the camp sell goods, from cigarettes to energy drinks, offer haircuts, or sell tea for 50 cents ($ 40) or simple meals. for a few euros in homemade restaurants.
The Prefecture of Calais has argued that these places should be demolished because they represent a parallel economy that does not pay taxes and because they carry fire and sanitation risks.
Aid groups told the court that shops and restaurants are vital, arguing that the free meals offered by the pro-government association and other groups do not provide enough food for the growing camp population.
They commented that homemade shops and restaurants often provide shelter and free food for those in need.
The Lille court ruled that there was no legal basis to kick out the people running 72 homemade stores, but said the Calais prefecture&#39;s problems &quot;were fully understood.&quot;
Judge Jean-François Molla said groceries, cafes and restaurants played much more than just feeding people who &quot;live in extremely precarious conditions.&quot;
He said the spaces provided quiet meeting points for refugees and volunteers.
One place that was threatened with demolition was the camp&#39;s Jungle Book children&#39;s cafe, which is self-serving and offers 200 meals a day, English and French classes, and asylum counseling for hundreds of vulnerable unaccompanied minors at the camp.
More than 170,000 people signed a petition to protect the children&#39;s cafe.
A letter sent to the Guardian stated that closing it &quot;would be a disaster for these children, some of whom are no older than eight.&quot;
Two charities, Refugee Aid and L&#39;Auberge des Migrants on Friday estimated that the population at the Jungle camp had grown to surpass 9,000 - the highest ever - following a sharp increase in new arrivals over the summer.
