As a result of a series of explosions in resorts in Thailand, four people were killed.
Several explosions took place in southern Thailand on Friday morning.
The attack killed four people and injured 19.
The epicenter of the explosions fell on the city of Hua Hin.
Among the victims were ten foreigners, citizens of four states, there are no Russians among them.
None of the terrorist groups has yet taken responsibility for the incident, but the country&#39;s Interior Ministry hastened to declare that the Islamists were not involved in it.
Several people have already been detained on suspicion of organizing the explosions.
According to preliminary data from the local police, the scale and characteristics of the explosions indicate that they were directed against the military leaders of the country.
The attacks took place at popular tourist resorts including Patong Beach in the Phuket area and the cities of Hua Hin, Trang and Surat Thani.
After the military junta came to power in the country in 2014, economic growth fell from 7.2% (2012) to 2.8% (2015), but tourism remained one of the few industries showing development.
In 2016, 14 million people have already visited the country, which is 1.5 million more than in 2015.
The first suspects in the preparation and organization of the attacks have already been detained, police colonel Krisana Patanacharoen said.
It is too early to talk about goals, he added, but the country&#39;s Interior Ministry &quot;is confident that they are not connected with international extremist groups.&quot;
It is too early to draw conclusions, - said Mr. Patanacharoen. -
But we know for sure that these incidents are not directly related to any types of terrorism, in fact, they are local sabotage, and we are trying to establish the identities of those who were behind them.
The explosions took place on the birthday of Thailand&#39;s Queen Sikrit.
The Thai junta considers protecting the monarchy as one of its top priorities, so the incident is likely directed against it.
According to Sithichai Police General Shrisopacharoenrata, the bombs were detonated remotely within half an hour.
They were hidden inside trees in busy streets filled with tourists dining at restaurants.
It is already known that one of the four victims was a Thai girl selling street food.
The identities of the rest of the victims are still unknown, but it is known that they are residents of four foreign countries.
According to the Royal Thai Police, there are four German citizens, three Dutch nationals, two Italian citizens and an Austrian citizen.
There are no Russians among the victims of the explosions, the Rostourism press service reported.
Local experts also associate the explosions with the August 7 referendum, in which 61.4% of the country&#39;s population supported the draft of the new constitution.
It was prepared by a constitutional commission appointed by the military junta.
Voters had to decide whether they supported a system in which the upper house of parliament is fully appointed by the military and has a significant role in the election of the country&#39;s prime minister.
The new system has been adopted and will be tested for the first time in the 2017 parliamentary elections.
Recall that on May 22, 2014, a military coup took place in Thailand under the leadership of the country&#39;s army commander Prayut Chan-Och.
This step, he said, was prompted by the ongoing political crisis and the lack of progress in negotiations between the government and the opposition.
The military created the National Peace and Order Council, imposed curfews and censorship, and dispersed protesters and the upper house of parliament.
