In January 2014, in the center of Bangkok, near the Victory Monument, where one of the main protests took place, there were two explosions, as a result of which 28 people were injured, five of them were in critical condition.
The explosions were carried out by unknown persons on motorcycles.
Authorities have stepped up security in the capital and brought in military forces to protect the demonstrators.
Development of conditions began in Sukhoi Log.
As it became known to Kommersant, the government was asked to agree on the draft terms of the auction for the Sukhoi Log gold deposit, while maintaining two key restrictions.
It is proposed not to admit to the auction companies where 25% or more belongs to foreigners, and those applicants whose capital will not have at least 25% state participation.
Industry participants do not expect the government to rewrite the terms, noting that many players do not even risk taking on a complex and expensive project.
The auction can be announced in August and held in October.
The Ministry of Natural Resources submitted to the government a draft order and terms of the auction for the largest undeveloped gold deposit in Russia, Sukhoi Log (Irkutsk region, reserves and resources - 130 million ounces), two sources familiar with the situation told Kommersant.
The project was introduced on Wednesday evening, one of them specifies.
The Ministry of Natural Resources confirmed to Kommersant that the project has been submitted to the government.
Deputy Prime Minister Alexander Khloponin, who is in charge of subsoil use, told Kommersant that the project had not yet been received by the official’s office.
&quot;The auction may be announced in August, immediately after the government decree was issued, and taking into account the deadline for collecting applications from potential participants (at least 45 days), the tender may take place in October,&quot; the Ministry of Natural Resources said.
According to Kommersant&#39;s information, the project retained two key requirements for potential participants, spelled out in the version that was sent for approval to ministries and federal executive authorities in July (Kommersant has it).
The first is the presence of at least 25% state participation in the candidates&#39; capital.
The second is the denial of access to the auction for companies controlled by foreign investors, based on the understanding of Federal Law No. 57 on foreign investment in strategic companies.
According to the two articles of the Federal Law specified in the draft, as Kommersant already wrote on August 2, companies whose beneficiaries (25% of shares and above) are not tax residents of the Russian Federation or have dual citizenship may not be allowed to participate in the auction.
The government has the right to impose such restrictions, since Sukhoi Log belongs to the subsoil of federal significance (reserves over 50 tons of gold).
The Ministry of Natural Resources confirmed that the project &quot;contains restrictions on the admission of foreign companies,&quot; but declined to comment on the details pending a government order.
The demand for state participation in the capital of the auction participants was put forward by the Irkutsk region, Kommersant was told in the Ministry of Natural Resources in December 2015 and later confirmed by the regional governor Sergei Levchenko, noting that it was sent to the Ministry of Natural Resources by his predecessor Sergei Eroshchenko, who &quot;had agreements on investment projects with Rostec. &quot;&quot;.
Kommersant&#39;s interlocutors do not specify who lobbied for the restriction on the admission of foreigners.
“But this is in the spirit of the times: not to give up control of the largest gold deposit in Russia against the background of Western sanctions,” says the source of Kommersant, who is familiar with the preparation of the auction.
The head of the Ministry of Natural Resources, Sergei Donskoy, announced on August 1 that foreigners &quot;can join the consortium&quot; if the applicants attract them &quot;as a financial structure, technological partners.&quot;
Kommersant&#39;s interlocutors consider it unlikely that the government will adjust the conditions.
The main contender for Sukhoi Log in the industry is considered the consortium of the largest gold miner of the Russian Federation PJSC Polyus, controlled by the son of Suleiman Kerimov Said, and Rostec.
As Kommersant wrote, in July the partners created the SL Zoloto JV, where Polyus has 51% of the shares, and the Rostec RT-GR structure has 49%.
Rostec declined to comment, while Polyus told Kommersant that they were &quot;undoubtedly interested in this asset&quot; and have all the necessary competencies and resources for its development.
&quot;But the final decision on the possibility and format of our participation will be made after the announcement of the conditions,&quot; added Polyus.
ALROSA may participate in the auction, but the decision is up to the Russian government, sources told Kommersant.
Russian GV Gold and Canadian Kinross, which are developing assets in Chukotka, announced the possibility of participating in the development of Sukhoi Log, while Polymetal and Nordgold, according to Kommersant, are not interested in the asset.
In December 2015, the head of the Union of Gold Producers of the Russian Federation, Sergei Kashuba, estimated Kommersant&#39;s investments in Sukhoi Log at $ 2.5-4 billion.
