The largest M&amp;A transaction has started in the pension market - KIT Finance Pension Administrator has launched the process of merging four controlled NPFs.
As a result, on the basis of Gazfond Pension Savings, an NPF will be created with an accumulation volume of about 373 billion rubles.
The launch of the procedure for merging four pension funds - KIT Finance, Promagrofond, Heritage and Gazfond Pension Savings - was announced yesterday by the owner of 100% of the funds, KIT Finance Pension Administrator.
&quot;The reorganization is carried out by agreement with the Central Bank, subject to the requirement of non-deterioration of the terms of existing contracts,&quot; the company said.
The amalgamation is carried out on the basis of &quot;Gazfond Pension Savings&quot;.
As the general director of this NPF Oleg Byaloshitsky notes, the pooling of funds allows solving several problems: expanding the geography of presence, concentrating resources for development, reducing costs, replicating the best practices of each of the funds and optimizing corporate governance.
According to him, the approximate date for the completion of the consolidation is the second quarter of 2017.
As a result of the merger, NPF Gazfond Pension Savings will become the largest player in the OPS market.
As of March 31, the volume of pension savings of the merging funds exceeded 373 billion rubles.
As follows from the reports on the funds&#39; website, the beneficiaries of their owner, KIT Finance Pension Administrator, are currently Anatoly Gavrilenko (through controlled LLCs he owns 65%) and NPF Gazfond (35%).
However, the group itself was launched much later than its competitors.
Thus, NPF Future, controlled by the O1 group, absorbed Stalfond at the beginning of this year.
At present, this combined NPF is joining the Uralsib and Russian Standard funds.
&quot;Consolidation into a single structure, in addition to reducing costs, is necessary for solving structural problems,&quot; said Nikolai Sidorov, general director of the NPF &quot;Future&quot;.
Active work on the consolidation of funds has been going on since April in the Safmar pension group - NPF Evropeyskiy, Obrazovanie i nauka, and Regionfond should join the NPF Safmar by the end of this year.
In 2017, NPF Doverie will join them.
&quot;The pooling of funds will have the effect of strengthening control over risks, operational processes and expenses,&quot; said the Safmar pension group.
The pause in the pooling of funds, which was endured by KIT Finance Pension Administrator, can be caused by several reasons, experts say.
Until recently, NPFs could not redeem more than 40% of the volume of the issue of infrastructure bonds, in which the group was actively placed.
After amending the Central Bank&#39;s resolution in March this year, there are no more such restrictions on a number of issuers that meet the requirements of the regulator.
If necessary, the entire issue can be redeemed by one major player, &quot;says Yuri Nogin, director of the ACRA financial institutions ratings group.
Several heads of NPFs from the top 15 in terms of assets, another possible reason for the pause is the separation of spheres of influence and, as a result, personnel appointments in a single fund, which the owners of the group had to agree on.
Yesterday Anatoly Gavrilenko was unavailable for comment.
The Gazfond NPF also did not respond to Kommersant&#39;s request.
While fund consolidation is time consuming and expensive, over the long haul it will make sense.
As noted by the general director of the consulting company Pension Partner Sergei Okolesnov, Gazfond Pension Savings has fewer outflows; the merger will help stabilize the base of the group&#39;s other funds.
In this case, the more successful experience of NPF KIT Finance and Promagrofond in building retail sales of OPS, as well as using more modern software will be in demand.
The Central Bank&#39;s requirements for the processes and personnel of NPFs are constantly growing, therefore, it is inexpedient to duplicate the infrastructure at four funds with a single investment policy, says Pavel Mitrofanov, Managing Director for Corporate Ratings at Expert RA.
&quot;The effect of reducing duplicate functions will definitely overlap the possible costs of the merger,&quot; says Mr. Mitrofanov.
Sergey Okolesnov estimates the costs of combining the four funds at 30-50 million rubles.
&quot;The costs of maintaining four funds of this size amount to about 400 million rubles per year, with consolidation in the medium term, the budget can actually be cut in half,&quot; Mr. Okolesnov is sure.
The kindest Disney movie &quot;Pete and His Dragon&quot; was released in Russia.
The beautiful views of New Zealand, the touching dragon, the sentimental story and country songs are enough to re-believe in old-fashioned magic, says ELENA KRAVTSUN.
The frightened baby was picked up by a dragon, who became a human baby both a gentle nanny and a devoted friend.
Pete names his friend Elliot, after the puppy from the book of fairy tales, plays catch-up with him and falls asleep in an embrace.
Six years later, he, overgrown and in a loincloth, can no longer be distinguished from another smart forest tomboy - Mowgli.
In this form, Pete is discovered by the red-haired female gamekeeper Grace (Bryce Dallas Howard), while the gang of Gavin (Karl Urban), her husband&#39;s brother, is aggressively cutting down the forest.
Now she will have to not only believe in the existence of the dragon, but also help save him.
Pete takes a crash course in being human surrounded by idyllic Americans who wear cowboy shirts, have a moral code in their hearts and smile more dazzling than any commercial.
No character looks or acts too horrible for the viewer to truly hate or fear him.
Even Gavin, who opened the hunt for an atypical inhabitant of the forests under his control, is far from an incorrigible villain.
The huge fluffy dragon also turned out to be not scary at all, with a good bulldog face, an airliner wingspan and the ability to become invisible.
The dragon hums funny, purrs, even grunts and, fortunately, does not speak, but all the time you want to stroke him, this compares favorably with all the famous cinematic dragons.
Elliot&#39;s visual image and demeanor provide such a high degree of emotional involvement that in the most tense moments, not only young spectators, but also adults begin to cry desperately into three streams.
Oaks Feegley is surprisingly good as a teenager in the role of Pete, torn between a possible family and a real friend.
And Robert Redford masterfully betrays the canonical grandfather, whom literally every child would be glad to have.
How did director David Lowry manage to make a fantastically cute remake of the forgotten Disney movie Pete&#39;s Dragon from 1977, mediocre from nose to tail and remembered only for a mix of animation and fiction, and make it the most soulful film of this summer?
Only a miracle helped.
In his painting, Lowry, in fact, took only two things from the original: the orphan Pete and the dragon.
Musical numbers and most of the strange jokes were left behind.
This kind fairy tale features features borrowed from &quot;Bambi&quot;, &quot;Alien&quot; and many other lovely children&#39;s pictures.
Disney continues to successfully expand its gallery of high-quality 21st century remakes.
Of course, Pete and the Dragon isn&#39;t nearly as overwhelmingly beautiful as The Jungle Book, and it doesn&#39;t have the skillful villain Cate Blanchett turns out to be as stepmother in the new Cinderella.
But this naive film is no less successful in helping to believe in miracles and goodness in the best Disney traditions.
By the way, director Lowry will receive the keys to Disney&#39;s magic castle once again - for an artistic film adaptation of the story about &quot;Peter Pan&quot;.
Working in tandem in Pete and His Dragon, David Lowry and screenwriter Toby Halbrooks entered an ambitious new project about an unmatched boy based on the tale of the same name by James Barry.
