Kommersantboscosport correspondent ALEXANDER ZILBERT lived the life of an Olympian in the Olympic Village, inspected the home of the Russian national team, dined in a local canteen and even passed the WADA test after that.
It seems that life here does not stop for a second.
Even at night.
The last starts sometimes end after midnight, after which the athletes need another hour and a half or two to return to the Olympic Village.
In addition, the settlement and eviction from the village is carried out without stopping, since some athletes finish their performances and leave Brazil, and some, on the contrary, just arrive here.
Well, already at 7:30 in the morning, the heads of all Olympic delegations stretch out to one of the temporary tents.
At these meetings, we usually discuss some operational everyday issues, - says Igor Kazikov, head of the sports delegation of the Russian Olympic team. - Despite the fact that the house in which ours were housed, consider it exemplary - it was commissioned one of the first and was shown to all the inspectors, even in it there are some imperfections every now and then.
Now there are problems with hot water, then, excuse me, with toilets.
We fought for purity for a long time.
At first, no one just came to clean.
Then the cleaners began to come, but they just poke some substance on the floor, and that&#39;s all.
Their floors, you see, are some kind of innovative.
Like, you can&#39;t wash them humanly.
Yes, we know these floors are ordinary laminate!
In general, we achieved a change in the cleaning company and now everything is OK with this.
The Olympic Village is a kind of Southern Butovo, a sleeping area, fenced off on one side by mountains, on the other - by an imposing moat, in places flooded with water.
Well, for reliability, there is still a two-meter iron fence around the entire perimeter, along which submachine gunners walk.
In total, the village can accommodate up to 17 thousand people in 3604 apartments located in 31 houses.
A huge Russian flag hangs on one of the 18-storey buildings - this house is completely dedicated to the needs of our team.
Looking at the small foyer at the entrance, you can immediately determine which problems are, apparently, the most pressing for the domestic team.
There are two announcements at the front desk: the printed &quot;Please don&#39;t throw paper in the toilet!&quot; and handwritten &quot;I will accept badges as a gift.
The stand itself is buried in booklets.
Their cheerful coloring contrasts with the titles of the brochures: &quot;A memo on infectious diseases for those traveling to Rio de Janeiro&quot;, &quot;First aid for drowning, foreign body in the respiratory tract, loss of consciousness - stages of cardiopulmonary resuscitation&quot;, &quot;First aid for burns, heatstroke, fractures and bleeding. &quot;
The text inside is generally encouraging.
For example, this: &quot;Infection is accompanied by fever and subsequent cure.
However, not everyone will have a favorable outcome.
Of course, the Russian national team has a medical center, which is ready to provide the residents of the house with qualified assistance at any time, including relaxing and sports massage.
Opposite the medical center is the actual headquarters of our delegation.
Next to the door is an inspiring poster &quot;In spite of everything, we will win!&quot;
And, of course, poems:
All arguments are absolute nonsense!
Only those who are afraid believe in them.
Let the smaller of us, the sweeter the taste of victories, Russia will not retreat, not break!
And for even greater upliftment of the spirits, there is an announcement: &quot;Dear brothers and sisters!
With the blessing of His Holiness Patriarch Kirill of Moscow and All Russia, Archpriest Andrei Vladimirovich Alekseev carries out spiritual care for the athletes of the Russian Olympic team.
You can order a prayer service and other services by phone ...
In general, on the territory of the village there is a Center for Meditation and Religious Rites for representatives of all confessions.
Well, the Russians, it turns out, are in a privileged position - they have their own chapel.
Due to the workload of the elevator from the ninth floor to the fourth, I decided to go down the stairs, which are recommended to be used during a fire.
And in the dark he stumbled over the bodies lying on her.
Apparently, these were the sleeping employees of the new cleaning company.
I suppose, ready to rush to cleaning innovative floors at any moment, they decided to arrange a quiet hour for themselves directly on the cold steps.
On the fourth floor, I met with an old acquaintance - Vitaly Fedorovich Dubko, the coach of our trampolines, who led them to Olympic gold 16 years ago in Sydney.
He and his pupil, European champion Yana Pavlova, kindly agreed to show their rooms.
Generally speaking, there is nothing to complain about, - the honored coach of Russia shares his impressions. - We live in twos, the beds, of course, are almost end-to-end, but this is not critical.
The bathroom is one for four, but spacious.
The wardrobe, of course, is ridiculous, made of fabric, it does not inspire confidence, but things can be put.
&quot;No, well, you are guessing, they have run out of tea!&quot; - tennis player Svetlana Kuznetsova, who I met in the main dining room, throws up her hands.
It is called the main one, if only because it represents an area of 2.7 thousand square meters. m and is ready to receive 5 thousand visitors at the same time.
Here they give out 60 thousand servings a day completely free of charge.
The menu options are: Best of Brazil, Cuisine of the World, Asian Food and Pizza, Pasta.
The last option, as I saw it, is very popular among our volleyball players.
At the same time, for example, I did not find any soups in any of the subdivisions of the giant restaurant.
What soups? - Kuznetsova is surprised. - No tea!
It&#39;s good that I brought some Chinese with me, a custard.
And a kettle.
But in general, so that you understand, the food on our courts is even worse.
Here at least something you can choose, despite the unbearable monotony.
I personally chose steamed cod and meatballs in tomato sauce.
Next to each dish there is a plate with its name in three languages - English, French and Portuguese, as well as indicating the nutritional value of the product and the presence of allergens in it.
Well, quite, I must admit, it was edible.
I don&#39;t even understand why there is such a line all the time at the local McDonald&#39;s.
Well-fed, relaxed, one might say &quot;warm&quot; athletes at the exit from the restaurant are waiting for our best friends - representatives of the World Anti-Doping Agency (WADA).
They lure you deftly - with a quiz, the winner of which gets a T-shirt.
They provoke, one might say!
To receive a gift, you must correctly answer at least eight questions out of ten.
Have questions in Russian! - the girl from WADA attacked me.
But she attacked the wrong one.
That is, I harnessed myself in a patriotic impulse, of course.
The situation became aggravated already on the second question: &quot;If I received a notification about the passage of the doping control, should I immediately go to the doping control point?&quot;
I settled on option B: &quot;No - I have one hour.&quot;
Lost, so to speak, vigilance.
I forgot that there is no need to expect indulgences from WADA.
In general, you must appear immediately.
Well, on the seventh stage of the quiz, my situation became completely critical.
For some reason I thought that if I find it difficult to maintain a balanced diet due to my busy schedule (and, by the way, it is difficult for me!), Then I can use supplements to get &quot;additional nutrients to increase my performance.&quot;
But no, they don&#39;t!
More precisely, the answer is formulated in such a way that it is not categorically prohibited, but strongly, in several sentences it is discouraged.
This WADA is playing unfairly!
How are you, Russia? - the quiz host asks mockingly.
There is nowhere to retreat - behind Efimov, Isinbaev and our whole bloodless team.
So I concentrated and with the last bit of strength won the unfortunate T-shirt.
Know, as they say, ours!
In a victorious mood, I wandered into the fitness center next door.
I got carried away with counting simulators.
Lost by 250.
I was surprised to note that not a single Russian athlete was found in this jumble of treadmills.
But maybe it is correct?
Let the one who does not know how to train train!
But in the nearby clinic one of our guys was sitting.
In line to see the optometrist.
Don&#39;t worry, not a shooter.
In the clinic, however, as well as throughout the village, wherever you spit, there is a machine for dispensing condoms.
It bears an inspiring message: &quot;Celebrate with a condom!&quot;
Then all that remains is to twist a piece of iron that resembles the handle of a door lock, and the condom, made of natural Amazon latex, readily falls out of the apparatus.
I took one for myself, as a keepsake.
The athletes will not lose anything - they were brought in 450 thousand of them.
Just for a festive and idle pastime, there is a whole entertainment center in the Olympic Village.
Near it, just in case, there is an educational sign reminding that the International Olympic Committee spends $ 3.25 million a day on athletes in various ways.
The center is awash with video games, billiard and tennis tables, table football and hockey, and some strange video simulators.
What is this? - I am interested in a friend in the uniform of the Ukrainian national team, who actively uses an outlandish toy.
I could, of course, just say that he doesn&#39;t want to talk to a man in the uniform of the Russian national team, and that&#39;s all.
Here, by the way, due to some strange coincidence of circumstances, the guys in the zhovto-blakitnoye are dazzling in the eyes.
The most playing team, it turns out.
It takes at least three hours to get around the whole village, looking into every corner of it.
But, if you walk, and not ride electric cars, you will see the house of the Canadian national team with an elk at the entrance and a tent with a recovery bath, and a ticket office, and a laundry, and a dry cleaner, and a hairdresser, and a flower shop, and a shop with everyday goods. consumption, and mail with unique stamps (only you still cannot wait out the queue of Chinese philatelists), and a bank, and a lost property, and a photo kiosk.
And late in the evening you, exhausted, will sit down near an olive tree hung with colorful ribbons in memory of friends and relatives of athletes who have left this world.
And you will, to the accompaniment of a machine randomly spraying liquid to kill insects, think about the eternal.
That is, about the Olympic movement.
Which in this village does not stop for a minute.
