The Spiritual Administration of Muslims (SAM) of Tatarstan refuses to use the Russian language in mosques.
Yesterday the plenum of the SAM ordered its imams to conduct Friday sermons only in Tatar, in order to force the young Tatars to &quot;learn their native language.&quot;
The department says that this &quot;in no way infringes&quot; the rights of Muslims of other nationalities.
Some mosques in Kazan complain that up to 60% of parishioners do not understand the Tatar language, including foreign students, migrants and the Tatars themselves.
The imams fear that their sermons in Tatar &quot;will not reach the entire audience.&quot;
Yesterday the plenum of the SAM of Tatarstan unanimously decided to hold Friday sermons in the republic&#39;s mosques only in the Tatar language.
As the mufti of Tatarstan Kamil Samigullin stated, this should become an incentive for young Tatars &quot;to learn their native language.&quot;
“For those who say it’s hard, in every big mosque we intend to organize Tatar language lessons absolutely free of charge,” Mr. Samigullin promised.
He added that &quot;the decision has already entered into force&quot; and today sermons in all mosques &quot;should already be in the Tatar language.&quot;
He recalled that the DUM of Tatarstan publishes the Shura magazine with typical sermons in the Tatar language.
An imam who does not speak Tatar well enough &quot;can thoroughly prepare for them.&quot;
DUM of Tatarstan unites more than a thousand parishes in all municipalities of the republic.
According to the mufti, Friday sermons in the districts are conducted exclusively in the Tatar language.
At the same time, in Kazan, in a number of mosques, the predominantly Russian language was previously used.
In particular, as the mufti pointed out, it was practiced in the Burnaevskaya mosque, Zakabannaya and Eniler.
However, Mr. Mukhametshin stressed, the leadership sets the task for all students to speak both state languages of the republic, regardless of nationality.
&quot;There can be no question of any infringement on the netatar Muslims,&quot; Mr. Mukhametshin emphasized, explaining that the sermon itself &quot;is not an obligatory, the main part of namaz.&quot;
At the same time, the prayer itself will continue to be read in Arabic, lectures and lessons in Russian will remain in mosques.
At the same time, Rafik Mukhametshin told Kommersant that there was no serious threat of ousting the Tatar language from mosques.
In addition to Russian and Tatar, other languages, for example, Uzbek or Tajik, according to his information, are not used in sermons in the republic.
The decision of the SAM was actively supported by the executive committee of the World Congress of Tatars (WKT).
The head of the VKT executive committee Rinat Zakirov told Kommersant: &quot;Mosques are an important part of our national life.&quot;
It would be sad if the Tatar language left this sphere.
He noted that preaching only in the Tatar language is &quot;the desire of the imams themselves,&quot; but the executive committee of the CGT &quot;considers it correct.&quot;
The imams interviewed by Kommersant, who preached in Russian, are ready to fulfill the decision of the SAM, but believe that the parishioners will have difficulties understanding the clergy.
Both Tatars and Russians go to the mosque.
Many do not understand the language.
They, of course, will be a little tight.
&quot;We&#39;ll have to rebuild,&quot; says Farhat Mavletdinov, imam of the Burnaevskaya mosque.
According to him, sermons in Russian are closer even to many Tatars, since &quot;Russian is in schools, in kindergartens, on the radio — everywhere from the very beginning.&quot;
However, he believes that the mosque will be able to continue the lessons and lectures in Russian, which are held on other days.
We rely on Allah.
Allah will show a way out of this situation, &quot;he concluded.
But about 60% of us do not know the Tatar language.
These are Uzbeks, Tajiks and Azerbaijanis.
A lot of foreign students come to us: Africans, Arabs.
“Therefore, we switched to Russian for four years,” says the imam.
He believes that sermons in the Tatar language will &quot;reach a narrower circle and will not reach the entire audience.&quot;
But we will obey the decision of the plenum.
Just the result of the sermons will be different.
But time will tell.
&quot;For me, for example, it will only be easier, because the Tatar language is my native language,&quot; concluded Gabdulla Galiullin.
Former director of the Federal Penitentiary Service put on trial
The Moscow Prosecutor&#39;s Office approved the indictment on the criminal case investigated by the Main Investigative Directorate of the ICR on embezzlement of budget funds allocated for the needs of the Federal Penitentiary Service of Russia.
The ex-head of the prison department, Alexander Reimer, and his deputy, who caused damage to the Federal Penitentiary Service in the amount of more than 2.7 billion rubles, will appear before the court.
The capital&#39;s prosecutor&#39;s office sent a criminal case against the former director of the Federal Penitentiary Service of Russia Alexander Reimer, his former deputy Nikolai Krivolapov, as well as the director of the FSUE Center for Information Technology Support and Communication of the Federal Service for the Execution of Punishments (FSUE CITOS) Viktor Definedov to the Zamoskvoretsky District Court.
Depending on the role and degree of participation in the commission of crimes, they are accused of the Main Investigative Directorate of the TFR in Moscow under Part 3 of Art. 285 of the Criminal Code of the Russian Federation (abuse of office, entailing grave consequences), part 4 of Art. 159 of the Criminal Code of the Russian Federation (fraud committed using one&#39;s official position, as part of an organized group, on an especially large scale).
In addition, Krivolapov is charged under Part 1 of Art. 222 of the Criminal Code of the Russian Federation (illegal acquisition and storage of ammunition).
According to the TFR, in 2010-2012, these persons fraudulently stole from the state treasury budget funds allocated by the Federal Penitentiary Service to provide the department with electronic monitoring systems for controlled persons, the so-called electronic bracelets.
To steal budget money, the group members developed a scheme, according to which the enterprise under their control, FGUP CITOS, with which the corresponding state contracts were concluded, produced technical means of control and supervision, including &quot;electronic bracelets&quot;, and sold them at prices that were inflated several times.
Despite the fact that FGUP TsITOS did not have production equipment, buildings, structures for the placement of production facilities, allowing to create a complete cycle of production of &quot;electronic bracelets&quot;, between it and the Federal Penitentiary Service of Russia were concluded five government contracts worth more than 3.3 billion rubles.
As a result of this scheme, the accounts of the Samara branch of the FSUE turned out to be more than 2 billion rubles, of which 1.2 billion rubles. was kidnapped.
According to the investigation, more than 140 million rubles. The cashed funds were received personally by Mr. Reimer in his office from one of the accomplices, the criminal case against which was separated into a separate proceeding.
Nikolai Krivolapov, who participated in the fraud, was found to have cartridges for the award pistol of unknown origin, which made it possible to bring additional charges against him.
In this case, the volume of which amounted to 133 volumes, the Federal Penitentiary Service filed a claim against the accused for compensation for material damage in the amount of 2.7 billion rubles.
Football player Hakan Shukur is suspected of involvement in the coup.
The Turkish authorities issued an arrest warrant for the former footballer and later MP Hakan Shukur and ransacked two of his family&#39;s homes.
Turkish football star of the 1990s and early 2000s, striker Hakan Shukur is wanted by the Turkish authorities in connection with the attempted coup d&#39;état last month.
The forward, who retired from his sports career in 2008, is accused of belonging to an &quot;armed terrorist group.&quot;
It is about the Hizmet movement, a society associated with the famous Turkish religious figure and opposition leader Fethullah Gülen.
It is his President Erdogan who considers the organizer of the attempted military coup on July 15.
Fethullah Gulen lives in the United States, the Turkish authorities are demanding his extradition.
According to local media reports, an arrest warrant for Hakan Shukur was issued today, and the police have already conducted searches in two houses that belong to the family of the former football player.
According to the investigation, in addition to Hakan Shukur himself, his father was part of Fethullah Gulen&#39;s organization.
However, neither the former football player himself, nor his relatives were there.
He and his family now live in the United States.
When he was a footballer, Hakan Shukur defended the colors of several Turkish clubs and played for the national team of the country.
He spent most of his career at Galatasaray.
The list of foreign clubs includes the Italian &quot;Torino&quot;, &quot;Inter&quot; and &quot;Palermo&quot;, as well as the English &quot;Blackburn&quot;.
