Military leadership distorted intelligence on ISIS, congressional commission reports
Officials from the U.S. Armed Forces Central Command have modified intelligence reports to present a more optimistic picture of the war against the Islamic State in Iraq and Syria than the events on the ground suggest, the congressional committee said in a report released Thursday.
An interim report by a task force set up by the Republican Chairmen of the House Armed Forces Committee, the Intelligence Committee, and the War Appropriations Subcommittee found &quot;widespread discontent&quot; among Central Command intelligence analysts who claim that leaders tweaked their assessments of US action victory over the Islamic State.
The Central Command, known as Centcom, is the military headquarters in Tampa, Florida that oversees US military operations in the Middle East and Central Asia.
&quot;Intelligence documents approved by the high command of the Centcom tended to provide a more optimistic portrayal of US counterterrorism activities than is confirmed by real data from the scene, and were consistently more optimistic than the analysis provided by other intelligence services,&quot; - said in a news release about the report ...
&quot;What happened at Centcom is unacceptable: when top management is presented with an unreliable analysis, our military suffers,&quot; said Rep. Ken Calvert, a Republican from California.
Problems with leadership in the Central Committee reach the very top of the organization.
The ten-page report details the flaws that continually surfaced in 2014 and 2015 in the description and analysis of American actions to train the Iraqi armed forces provided by Central Command.
While it does not provide conclusive evidence that members of the Obama administration&#39;s leadership ordered the reports to be falsified, he argues that analysts felt that the Centcom leadership was forcing them to present a more optimistic view of the threat from the Islamic State, also known as ISIL or ISIL.
&quot;Throughout the first half of 2015, many of the press releases, statements and testimonies from Central Command in Congress were significantly more optimistic than actual events,&quot; the report said.
For example, a Centcom official publicly stated that a major military attack aimed at returning Mosul could begin as early as April or May 2015.
Mosul, Iraq&#39;s second largest city, remains under the control of the Islamic State.
&quot;After months of investigation, we know for sure,&quot; Rep. Mike Pompeo, a Republican from Kansas, said in a statement.
From mid-2014 to mid-2015, the most senior intelligence officials at US Central Command forged the command&#39;s intelligence documents to downplay the ISIS threat in Iraq.
Republicans formed a task force when they learned that analysts had expressed concern that intelligence about the Islamic State was being falsified.
As the investigation progresses, more detailed data will follow the report released on Thursday.
An additional, currently unfinished investigation into Centcom&#39;s intelligence is being conducted by the Chief Inspector of the Department of Defense.
Democratic representatives on the House Intelligence Committee of the US Congress released their own data Thursday, which is consistent with some of the findings of the Republican task force.
“Between 2014 and 2015, Centcom created an overly closed procedure for producing intelligence assessments regarding ISIS and the Iraqi security forces,” Rep. Adam B. Schiff, the Democratic Party&#39;s chief spokesman on the committee, said in a statement.
The procedure, according to Schiff, &quot;stalled the release of intelligence documents&quot;, damaged the morale of analysts and &quot;did not sufficiently reflect divergent views.&quot;
But Schiff and the Democrats say they have found no evidence that the White House tried to force Central Committee analysts to tailor their conclusions to &quot;a given or political interpretation.&quot;
The preliminary findings of the Congressional investigation were released on Tuesday by The Daily Beast.
Last August, The New York Times reported on the existence of an investigation by the Pentagon Inspector General following complaints from Centcom analysts.
Lt. Commander Patrick Evans, a Pentagon spokesman, said in a statement that the Department of Defense would not comment on the Congressional report while the Inspector General&#39;s investigation continued.
But he said that &quot;experts sometimes disagree on the interpretation of complex data, and the intelligence services and the Ministry of Defense welcome a healthy dialogue on these vital national security topics.&quot;
The ramifications of the investigation go beyond the question of whether the American bombing campaign in Iraq and Syria is achieving its goals (as more and more Defense officials are now claiming).
But last year&#39;s statements cast doubt on whether President Obama can rely on Central Command to provide accurate assessments of military operations in Iraq, Afghanistan, Libya and other crisis areas.
Criticism of intelligence on the Islamic State echoes controversy more than a decade ago, when Central Committee intelligence analyst Gregory Hooker wrote a research article claiming that the administration of President George Walker Bush, over protest from many analysts, had come out in support of small numbers of troops in Iraq and didn&#39;t think about what would follow the 2003 invasion.
Hooker also played a key role in the Islamic State intelligence protest.
Last year, officials said Hooker&#39;s team concluded that despite public statements to the contrary, airstrikes against Islamic State-owned refineries did not significantly worsen the terrorist group&#39;s financial position because it built temporary refineries. to sell oil on the black market.
But the discovery was not circulated outside of Central Command, the Times reported in September.
The then commander of the Centcom, General Lloyd J. Austin III, was criticized last year after testimony in the Senate, which many MPs considered overly optimistic about the war.
General Austin resigned in April and was replaced in General Command. Joseph L. Votel.
