In the midst of the frenzy of the Olympic Games - the Zen of trampoline jumping
Wherever you are, no matter what time it is, this is the Olympics.
Events in Rio de Janeiro seem constant and inevitable, a frenzied mix of competition and drive.
It is as if the Olympic flame itself is that burning torch that is transmitted from an archer to a swimmer, to a gymnast, to a triathlete.
You can&#39;t turn on the TV, read the newspaper, or overhear your neighbors taking turns in a cafe and not hear about Simone Biles, Katie Ledecky, or the feud between Michael Phelps and Chad de Clos.
And then there&#39;s Logan Dooley.
Dooley, a first-time Olympian, dimpled handsome man, could very well be among the prime-time celebrities promoted by sponsors and life-affirming commercials if he were a swimmer, gymnast, or even fencer.
But Dooley, 28, from Lake Forest, California, is competing for gold in the Olympic trampoline competition.
The Olympic flame does not cover all events in the same way.
Further from the center, partly in the shade, there are sports that are not generally recognized: air pistol shooting, archery, badminton, taekwondo.
Breaststroke will always be with us, his long reign.
But if I am allowed to shyly speak out in defense of my personal addiction, let me draw your attention to the modest charm of trampoline jumping.
Although trampoline jumping has been an Olympic sport since 2000, when it debuted at the Sydney Games, it has received so little acceptance over the past 16 years that many people I interviewed were not aware that it was an Olympic sport at all.
This may be regional ignorance.
Although the United States sent athletes to competitions, they never won medals in trampoline jumping, and their athletes did not make it to the finals until 2012.
The Chinese and Russians, as a rule, share among themselves men&#39;s awards, while the Chinese and Canadians share women&#39;s awards.
Dong Dong of China and Rosie McLennan of Canada will defend their London gold medals this year.
But jumping on a trampoline has an outsider charm, in part because for the unenlightened ear it is more associated with a circus college than with the Olympic Games.
Here I must confess that I am not an expert, but only a down-to-earth enthusiast.
They do have comic potential - it&#39;s a caricature of endless leaps - but also the grace of gymnastics and diving, two sports that they mostly combine.
The word &quot;trampoline&quot; comes from the Spanish word &quot;el trampolín&quot;, which means &quot;diving board&quot;.
The contenders jump on a giant trampoline, soaring nearly 30 feet into the air, and must perform a series of acrobatic tricks (twists, bends, and flips) before finally landing on their feet.
They are judged on performance, difficulty and &quot;flight time&quot; according to the official Olympic Games program.
Thirty-two athletes from 17 countries, 16 men and 16 women, will compete in Rio.
The most common Olympic course is forward.
Medal contenders must go further, faster, higher and higher in pursuit of gold, sometimes to the finish line, and sometimes back and forth, back and forth across the field.
They are striving not only for the finish line or the starting wall, but also, in full view of the TV cameras, for another tantalizing milestone: a world or Olympic record.
This stubborn aspiration is noble, admirable, even fanatical - and it is enough to make even the viewer cry.
But it is, in my opinion, somewhat tiresome when watching the Games.
From him jumping on a trampoline gives a break.
The direction of the trampoline is up.
Moving forward is not the goal.
He or she jumps, appears weightless, like an astronaut, flies up, then down, then effortlessly up again.
And in them, of course, it is not without competition or difficulties, but during the entire program there is no mad zeal for the finish, no long jumps, only a wondrous, graceful disappearance of time and gravity.
It is the closest Olympic sport to Zen.
The women&#39;s qualifiers, followed by the finals, will take place on Friday afternoon, broadcast at 1pm ET; men - on Saturday, also at one o&#39;clock.
NBC will air the finale as part of the daytime program starting at 2:00 pm on both days.
In the midst of the Olympic madness, a calm, beautiful moment is expected, which can be easily overlooked in a common junkyard.
And if a rise in consciousness can only be achieved by exposing male athletes to coveted views and objectification - as male gymnasts from the United States recently suggested, according to the Wall Street Journal, - Dooley is just waiting for her new admiring crowd of fans.
Generation protests in Ethiopia, longtime US ally
Violent protests in Ethiopia
Demonstrators demanding political change in Ethiopia faced fierce opposition from the government.
Eyewitnesses say dozens of protesters were fatally injured in clashes with police.
Is Ethiopia really on the brink of a split?
Over the past decade, it has been one of the most stable countries in Africa, a staunch ally of the West with a rapidly growing economy.
But in recent months, anti-government protests have rocked the country, spreading to more and more territories.
In the past week alone, thousands have taken to the streets demanding radical political change.
Human rights defenders said the government&#39;s response was brutal.
Eyewitnesses claimed that dozens of unarmed demonstrators were shot and killed by police officers.
Videos from protest sites, allegedly filmed late last year or early this year, show security officers beating young men with sticks when they were pushed against a wall.
The top United Nations human rights official is now calling for a thorough investigation.
“It has always been difficult to keep this country from falling apart, and it will be even more difficult in the future,” said Rashid Abdi, head of the Horn of Africa project at the international crisis research group.
Ethiopia is the second most populous country in Africa after Nigeria, and its stability is supported by the West.
The US military and intelligence services work closely with Ethiopians to combat terrorist threats in the region, especially in Somalia, and virtually no country in Africa receives such support from the West.
Ethiopia&#39;s economy is growing at an impressive rate.
Its infrastructure has improved significantly - there is even a new commuter train in the capital, Addis Ababa.
And its streets are generally quiet, safe and clean.
However, Ethiopia was hardly a model of democracy - human rights organizations constantly mention government repression - opposition on the territory of the state was suppressed, due to the fact that dissidents were effectively silenced.
Many of them were exiled, imprisoned, killed or exiled to remote deserts.
But that could change.
&quot;If people are constantly suppressed and left with no choice but to protest, there will be an uprising,&quot; said Seyum Teshome, a lecturer at a university in central Ethiopia.
All young people are protesting.
The generation is protesting.
Complaints are numerous, ranging from land use to a government coalition&#39;s takeover of power.
Following a widely criticized election last year, the government party and its allies have completely ousted the opposition and now control 100 percent of Parliament.
At the same time, tensions are growing along the border with Eritrea; fighting over this vague, contested border claimed hundreds of lives in June.
Analysts fear that secessionist groups that have been more or less wiped out in recent years, such as the Oromo Liberation Front or the Ogaden National Liberation Front, may try to exploit the unrest and rearm.
A number of factors explain why bitter feelings that have been simmering in the depths of the soul for several years now flare up.
The first, it would seem, is completely harmless: smartphones.
In the last couple of years alone, a large number of Ethiopians have been able to communicate on social media as cheap smartphones have become mainstream and internet service has improved.
Even when the government closes access to Facebook and Twitter, as it often happens, especially during protests, many people still find the opportunity to communicate through proxy servers that hide where they are.
Several young Ethiopians said that was how they organized for the protests.
Second, there is more solidarity between Oromo and Amhara, the two largest Ethiopian ethnic groups.
Oromo and Amhara are not natural allies.
For centuries, Amhara, from Ethiopia&#39;s predominantly Christian highlands, has thrived in politics and business, exploiting Oromo, many of whom are Muslim and live in low-lying areas.
But that is also changing.
“We will act together under a single leadership,” said Oromo leader Mulat Gemechu.
The largest protests took place in the Amhara and Oromo districts.
Many in Amhara and Oromo feel that Ethiopia is unfairly dominated by members of the Tigray ethnic group, which makes up about 6 percent of the population and which controls the military and intelligence services, trade and politics.
The third cause of unrest is the loss of Meles Zenawi.
Meles, a former rebel leader, served as Ethiopia&#39;s prime minister for 17 years, until his death from an unknown illness in 2012.
He was considered a tactical genius, a man who could foresee danger.
Analysts say he was particularly adept at detecting early signals of discontent and using scouts to gain intelligence and neutralize opponents.
&quot;The current regime lacks common sense,&quot; said Abdi, a conflict analyst.
Ethiopia&#39;s new prime minister, Hailemariam Desaleni, appeared out of nowhere and took Meles&#39; place.
Unlike Meles, who was originally from the Tigray region of northern Ethiopia, Hailemariam is a Southerner.
Analysts say he is not trusted by the security services controlled by Tygra.
Many fear that this will lead to more bloodshed as a result.
Ethiopia last experienced such unrest in 2005, after thousands of people protested against what analysts said was apparently an election that the government screwed up and then falsified the results.
In the ensuing repression, many Protestants were killed, albeit in fewer numbers than in recent months, and this period of unrest passed relatively quickly.
Development experts praised Ethiopia&#39;s leaders for forward-thinking infrastructure developments such as a new intercity train and significant gains in poverty reduction.
But this has clearly not stopped the rise of domestic discontent with the Ethiopian government.
And it takes on a dangerous ethnic form.
Last month, protesters in Gondar, a city in Amhara, attacked Tygrai-owned businesses, and anti-Tygrai hatred on social media is pervasive.
Analysts say the protesters are embarrassing the United States and other Western allies.
The US government has used Ethiopia as a base for unmanned flights over neighboring Somalia, although it recently announced it had closed the base.
On the one hand, it is clear that the West wants to support democracy, but on the other hand, it does not want its ally to lose power in an already unstable region.
&quot;And this tightrope will be difficult to walk on,&quot; Abdi said.
