Depressive Depression Food in &quot;Heavy Meal&quot;
In March 1933, shortly after taking office, Franklin Delano Roosevelt sat down to dine in the Oval Office.
As a foodie, President Roosevelt loved Fifth Avenue trendy dishes such as foie gras and Maryland turtle soup.
His menu that day was more modest: stuffed eggs in tomato sauce, mashed potatoes, and prune pudding for dessert.
“It was an act of culinary solidarity with people who were suffering,” said Jane Siegelman.
Her husband Andrew Coe added: &quot;It was also a message to Americans about how to eat.&quot;
The couple, who live in Brooklyn Heights, are experts in food history.
Coa&#39;s latest book, Chinese Stew, focused on Chinese food in America, and Siegelman told the story of living in a rented apartment on the Lower East Side through food in her book 97 Orchard Street.
Their new collaboration, &quot;Heavy Meal,&quot; to be published Tuesday by Harper, is the story of American food during the Great Depression.
In a somewhat culinary solidarity of their own, they met the reporter for dinner at Eisenberg&#39;s Sandwich Shop, a tiny, unpretentious eatery in the Flatiron Quarter that has been operating since the 1929 Stock Crash.
Siegelman, 54, ordered a cream cheese and olive sliced sandwich, while Coe, 57, ordered a turkey, mashed potatoes, and a vegetable mix.
When the reporter ordered the meatloaf, the couple found it a good starting point for a discussion about Depression-era food.
&quot;The rolls were in high demand,&quot; Siegelman said.
There was peanut roll, liver roll, bean roll.
They were made from the main ingredient and cheap products that allowed the ingredient to be stretched.
Imagine eating as many peanuts as you need for dinner.
Coe winced.
“He must have been lying like a stone in his stomach,” he said.
In the years before the Depression, the American table, especially in the countryside, was a buffet.
Groups of women cooked for the male farm workers, and a freshly baked pie was served for breakfast, lunch and dinner.
It was the Americans who sent food to the starving Europeans during the First World War. &quot;A Heavy Meal&quot; describes how a country coped with what was suddenly no longer a land of plenty.
“It was a time when food became a central, challenging topic for Americans,” Coe said, explaining why he and his wife decided to write about it.
Equally challenging was the new budgetary diet: mysterious dishes such as rolls and casseroles became staples; A casserole is &quot;a great way to dispose of leftovers,&quot; Siegelman observed, &quot;because chefs could hide unappetizing ingredients under a thick layer of sauce.
Fresh fruit has been replaced with cheaper dried fruit.
Meat, the staple of American food for many years, has become an economically distributed luxury.
People have tried strange mixtures because energy and nutritional value have become more important than taste and even culinary common sense.
While doing research for a book that includes recipes, Siegelman prepared a dish from that era: baked onions stuffed with peanut butter.
&quot;This addition to the dining table was not a success,&quot; Coe said.
Siegelman added: &quot;It was very strange.&quot;
Peanut butter doesn&#39;t go well with baked onions.
This has been the case for many homemade recipes.
More than ever, and never since then, home economists - including Louise Stanley, chief of the federal Bureau of Home Economics from 1923 to 1943 - have ruled the country&#39;s dietary habits.
By publishing recipes and articles in newspapers and magazines, they advised women to become “budget makers,” rise to the challenge, and transform a burda like mashed spaghetti with carrots into delicious meals.
A &quot;hearty meal&quot; is a feast of curious historical facts.
Especially juicy stories about the government&#39;s reaction to starving citizens, for example, the position of President Herbert Hoover in the spirit of &quot;let them eat the pies.&quot;
Publicly extolling simple Iowa farm concoctions from his childhood days, he ate like the sophisticated millionaire he&#39;d become.
“He liked continental food like fish with cucumber sauce,” Coe said.
He ate in a practically gilded dining room, wearing a tuxedo.
He was fantastically out of touch with reality.
President Roosevelt could have made the same mistake if his wife, Eleanor, had not advised him to set an example with his own stomach.
As the book tells, Eleanor Roosevelt hired a housekeeper who was completely uninterested in taste, and this led the White House to &quot;eat not only the dullest food in Washington, but sometimes the most disgusting cooked.&quot;
Many of the culinary techniques of the Depression era were forgotten once the country was back on its feet.
Their legacy is our continued focus on calories and nutrition, Siegelman says, and how science has been used in food preparation.
The couple say that while writing the book, they better understood the eating habits of Siegelman&#39;s mother - that she could not throw food, for example.
“She was seriously afraid of being careless about food,” Coe said.
Siegelman recalls: &quot;She poisoned people in all seriousness.&quot;
There was one unpleasant incident with profiteroles.
When the plates at Eisenberg&#39;s were empty, she and Coe pulled out a dessert they had made at home: the prune dessert President Roosevelt had for lunch.
&quot;It&#39;s called prune mousse,&quot; Siegelman said, adding that it was a common practice to give humble recipes catchy names.
There was no whipped cream, only prunes, some flour, sugar, water, and cinnamon.
Everyone reluctantly dipped the spoon into a viscous, brown, sticky substance.
Surprisingly, it wasn&#39;t bad.
Coe has asked for supplements twice.
In the voice of a confident budget planner, he told his wife, &quot;A little chopped walnuts would be nice.&quot;
