NASA&#39;s climate model: Venus was once habitable
Venus may have once been habitable, according to estimates from NASA&#39;s new climate model.
Scientists at the Goddard Space Research Institute of NASA have developed a model to explore Venus&#39;s past using tools and algorithms similar to those used by climatologists.
The model was developed to determine if Venus, with its hot, anhydrous surface and an oversaturated carbon dioxide atmosphere, could ever have had Earth-like conditions.
Scientists have previously suggested that Venus&#39;s low rotational speed is due to its dense atmosphere.
But the latest modeling suggests that Venus could probably have a thin Earth-like atmosphere and still rotate slowly.
The model also looked at the topography of early Venus.
The planet likely had more arid regions than Earth, but it once had enough water and enough geographic variability to create conditions for life and prevent rapid evaporation.
Early Venus also benefited from the sun, which was 30 percent dimmer.
&quot;According to the GISS model, Venus&#39;s slow rotation exposes its daytime side to the sun for almost two months at a time,&quot; GISS scientist Anthony Del Genio explained in a press release.
This warms the planet&#39;s surface and produces rain, which creates a thick cloud layer that acts as an umbrella protecting the planet&#39;s surface from a significant portion of the sun&#39;s heat.
The result is average climatic temperatures that, surprisingly, are several degrees colder than today on Earth.
The model shows the history of Venus, similar to the development that experts in planetary studies previously assumed.
Even though Venus may once have been inhabited, it has been exposed to too much heat and ultraviolet radiation for billions of years.
Its oceans have evaporated and its water vapor has been burned out by ultraviolet radiation.
When its hydrogen evaporated, there was only a dense atmosphere of carbon dioxide with a deadly greenhouse effect - that is, Venus as we know it today.
The researchers shared the results of their new climate model for Venus in Geophysical Research Letters.
