Kepler measures the speed of rotation of stars in the Pleiades cluster
The last mission of the Kepler space telescope has helped astronomers compile the most complete catalog of the speeds of rotation of the stars in the Pleiades cluster.
The new data is helping astronomers understand why the stars in the cluster rotate at different speeds, as well as how periods of rotation relate to planet formation.
“We hope that by comparing our results with other star clusters, we can learn more about the relationship between a star&#39;s mass, its age, and even the history of its solar system,” said Louise Riball, Research Fellow at the Center for Infrared Processing and Analysis at California Institute of Technology.
The Pleiades Cluster is 445 light years from Earth.
Many of the stars in the cluster are now just reaching maturity; they were born about 125 million years ago.
They&#39;re spinning as fast as they never will.
At their peak rotational speeds, these maturing stars eject large amounts of stellar wind.
Traveling through the magnetic fields of stars, these winds have a braking effect on the stars.
As the star ages, its rotation speed begins to slow down.
Kepler measures the speed of rotation of each star, tracking the time between the appearance of recognizable star spots, such as sunspots.
The most recent catalog of rotation rates suggests that more massive stars rotate more slowly than less massive stars.
Riball compares stars to dancers: the larger ones pirouette more slowly than the smaller ones.
&quot;In the &#39;ballet&#39; of the Pleiades, we observe that those that rotate slowly are usually more massive, while those that rotate faster tend to be very light stars,&quot; Riball said.
Since the Pleiades cluster is so close, it serves as an ideal space laboratory for comparing the properties of stars with rotation rates.
&quot;The Pleiades star cluster provides a starting point for theoretical models of the rotation of stars, both younger and older,&quot; said Riball.
We still want to learn a lot about how, where and why the stars slow down their speed of rotation and hang their &quot;dancing shoes&quot; on a nail, figuratively speaking.
Riball and her colleagues have detailed their latest analysis of the Pleiades&#39; rotation rates in three new articles, soon to be published in the Astronomical Journal.
