Squeezed between Angola and South Africa, Namibia has suffered greatly during the long struggle against apartheid.
However, since independence from South Africa in 1990, this country of 2.4 million has made tremendous strides, especially in the past few years.
The main reason for Namibia&#39;s success is that the government pays great attention to education.
While people in developed countries take free primary and secondary education for granted, in many poor countries, secondary and even primary schools require tuition fees.
Moreover, governments are often advised to introduce &quot;cost recovery&quot; tuition fees.
However, in Namibia, primary schooling is free.
Moreover, since 2015, secondary education has also become free.
The country&#39;s authorities are also actively working in other important areas.
Efforts to eradicate malaria have reduced the number of annual cases of the disease by 97% over the past ten years.
Contrary to the international trend of rising inequality, it is declining in Namibia.
Compared to 1993, the Gini coefficient, a standard measure of inequality in the distribution of income, has dropped 15 points.
Then, 23 years ago, this figure was one of the highest in the world.
And the poverty rate fell from 69% in 1993 to less than 30%.
The number of people living in extreme poverty (on less than $ 1.90 a day) also fell, from nearly 53% to less than 23%.
Namibia also has the highest free speech rating in Africa, according to Reporters Without Borders.
The country is well ahead of the United States and other wealthy nations.
In addition, the country has a favorable rating - one of the highest in Africa - on Transparency International&#39;s Corruption Perceptions Index.
Even now, when commodity prices are falling, Namibia manages to maintain high growth rates.
At the same time, the ratio of debt to GDP is about 25%, which is less than 1/3 of the debt level in the United States and most European countries.
Of course, Namibia has some problems.
The unemployment rate, at least according to traditional methods of assessment, is still quite high - almost 28%.
And like other countries in the region, Namibia has a high incidence of HIV / AIDS - almost 17% of the population is infected.
The World Bank ranks Namibia as an upper middle-income country, but the authorities insist that their country is in fact a developing country.
Namibia certainly faces some of the challenges that are inherent in underdeveloped economies.
The state has to develop a very large and arid country with a small population.
Isolated nomadic hunter-gatherer tribes live in the country&#39;s deserts, which in one way or another must be integrated into modern society without losing their identity.
Integrating people who were on the periphery of the world economy a quarter of a century ago is not an easy task for any country.
For Namibia, this is even more difficult: just like any other country in the world, it is facing the effects of climate change.
However, Namibia did not think to give up, the country is solving the problems it faces.
Almost immediately after independence, the authorities set about creating a diversified economy and a cohesive society.
Significantly, competing political factions have come together to work for the common good.
Indeed, Namibia provides cheap medical care not only for its own citizens, but also for its neighbors.
About 15-20% of visitors to medical institutions in the northern regions of Namibia are Angolan citizens.
No one in Namibia talks about building a wall that would separate the country from its poor and corrupt neighbors.
The Namibians realized that they did not choose their neighbors, and therefore decided not to conflict with them, but to cooperate - to share scarce water resources, take part in regional medical projects, encourage investment and student exchange.
Moreover, the Namibian government has rightly judged that rich natural resources can easily become a curse, contributing to the enrichment of the few at the expense of the many.
The authorities understand that the revenues from Namibia&#39;s natural wealth need to be invested in infrastructure and manufacturing facilities.
They also recognize that it would be irresponsible not to seek the maximum profit from the sale of a country&#39;s resources, and are reviewing investment laws and mining contracts to ensure that this is the case.
Transparency is critical to this process, which is why strong government support for free speech is so important.
