Many have heard of the &quot;Gold of Varna&quot; - the oldest gold objects created by man (4600 - 4200 BC).
Perhaps this was the loudest archaeological sensation of the 1970s: in Bulgaria, during the excavations of the Varna necropolis, a fantastic amount of gold artifacts was found - more than three thousand with a total weight of 6 kilograms.
From only one burial site, known as &quot;Grave No. 43&quot;, 990 gold objects with a total weight of more than 1.5 kg were recovered.
However, the official status of the oldest gold in the world may soon pass to a nondescript-looking bead found by archaeologists in July this year.
And again in Bulgaria - in a prehistoric settlement known as Tell Yunatsite.
Unlike Varna, the port city, Tell Yunatsite is located far from the sea, near the village of Yunatsite, Pazardzhik region.
The bead is a gold strip rolled into a ring.
Yavor Boyadzhiev, head of the Tell Yunatsite excavation, dated the find to 4600 BC and stated that it was at least 200 years older than the gold of Varna.
The treasures of Varna, we recall, date back to approximately the same period, 4600 - 4200 years. BC.
There is currently no technology to date metal with impeccable accuracy.
Where is the confidence in which gold is more ancient?
Apparently Professor Boyadzhiev knows more than he told Reuters: &quot;I am quite sure that Yunatsite&#39;s gold is older than Varna&#39;s gold.&quot;
This is a find of extreme importance: it looks like a tiny object, but it is large enough to take its rightful place in history.
In an interview with Reuters, Boyadzhiev said that in the near future, scientists will analyze the composition of the metal, and also re-and more thoroughly study the archaeological layer where the gold artifact was found.
This will help date the bead as accurately as possible.
The location of the find also explains a lot.
Tell Yunatsite is a famous settlement, even if you have never heard of it.
Nowadays Tell Yunatsite is considered the oldest &quot;city&quot; in Europe.
Tell was founded by the descendants of people who migrated to Europe from Anatolia (modern Turkey) in the 7th millennium BC.
Over the next centuries, metal processing developed rapidly in this region, from the development of the first metallurgical skills to the creation of a full-fledged industry.
In Russian historiography, this archaeological community has a special name: Balkan-Carpathian metallurgical province.
In the 5th millennium BC, urban-type settlements began to appear around the centers of metalworking.
Now they are called the oldest cities in Europe.
Of these, Tell Yunatsite is perhaps the oldest, as artifacts from 4900 BC were found here.
I would call Tell Yunatsite the prototype of the modern city, although it is a very ancient settlement, even in comparison with Mesopotamia.
&quot;This place is a thousand years older than Sumer,&quot; says Boyadzhiev, referring to the conventional wisdom that urban culture originated in southern Mesopotamia - modern Iraq.
The first cities in the usual sense of the word arose there.
Tell Yunatsite has been excavating since 1976.
During this time, archaeologists have excavated almost 12 hectares, which is about a third of the estimated total area of the settlement.
The remains of a fortress wall, which once reached three meters in height, were found.
Little has survived from houses and workshops, but archaeologists clearly distinguish between streets, public buildings, dense urban development, a &quot;business center&quot; and residential outskirts.
Tell Yunatsite is often called the &quot;Bird City&quot;: dozens of clay figurines of birds have been found here.
All birds are depicted in a state of rest, hence the assumption arose that they were not decorative objects, but an object of local cult.
The &quot;Bird City&quot; was destroyed around 4100 BC - possibly by Indo-European tribes who came from the northeast.
The nomads had no cities, but they had horses and weapons.
The three-meter fortress walls did not stop them.
Archaeologists have uncovered obvious signs of a brutal massacre: the remains of old people, women and children with traces of wounds inflicted by battle axes were found inside the houses.
New finds and new facts appear every year, changing the usual ideas about the ancient history of mankind.
Bulgarian archaeologists are increasingly talking not about individual cultures, but about the &quot;lost&quot; first civilization of Europe, which originated in the Balkans.
A powerful incentive in the search for this civilization was the &quot;gold of Varna&quot; found relatively recently, in 1972.
It is logical that the golden luxury of Varna should have been preceded by something - something like a tiny gold bead created in Tell Yunatsite.
